so lets say I have 3 node consul cluster and all the nodes crashes, but I have the consul data dir for all those nodes and the last snapshot. I have to bring the new 3 nodes with new ip address. what recovery procedure I should follow?

Because you are moving to completely new IP addresses, this is the exact scenario where simply dropping in the old data directories will fail. The servers will boot up, read their saved Raft state, and endlessly try to contact the dead, old IPs.

Since you have both the data directories and a snapshot, you actually have two different paths to recovery. Here is how to execute both, so you can choose the one that fits your needs.

Option 1: The peers.json Method (Recommended for Zero Data Loss)
Use this method if you want the cluster restored to the exact millisecond it crashed. By using the data directories, you preserve all state that happened after your last snapshot.

Step 1: Stage the Data
Install Consul on the 3 new servers, but do not start the Consul service yet. Copy your backed-up data directories to the configured data_dir path on all 3 new servers.

Step 2: Gather the Node IDs
Consul needs to map the existing Node IDs to your new IP addresses. On each of the 3 new servers, read the node-id file inside the data directory:

Bash
cat /opt/consul/node-id
(Write these down and map them to the new IPs).

Step 3: Create the peers.json file
On every single server, navigate into the raft/ folder inside the data directory (e.g., /opt/consul/raft/). Create a file named peers.json containing the Node IDs and the new IP addresses (make sure to include the Raft port, default 8300):

JSON
[
  {
    "id": "node-id-from-server-1",
    "address": "192.168.1.10:8300",
    "non_voter": false
  },
  {
    "id": "node-id-from-server-2",
    "address": "192.168.1.11:8300",
    "non_voter": false
  },
  {
    "id": "node-id-from-server-3",
    "address": "192.168.1.12:8300",
    "non_voter": false
  }
]
Step 4: Start the Cluster
Start the Consul service on all 3 nodes.
When Consul boots, it will detect the peers.json file, safely overwrite the old Raft network topology with your new IPs, form a quorum, and elect a leader. (Consul will automatically delete the peers.json file once it is ingested).

Option 2: The Snapshot Method (The Easiest / Cleanest Path)
Use this method if you don't mind losing the delta of data between when the last snapshot was taken and when the cluster crashed. This avoids manually writing JSON files.

Step 1: Start a Fresh Cluster
Ignore the backed-up data directories entirely. Start the 3 new servers with completely empty data directories. Because they are fresh, they won't look for the old IPs. They will cleanly bootstrap, form a quorum on their new IPs, and elect a leader.

Step 2: Restore the Snapshot
Once the new cluster is healthy and has a leader, take your snapshot file and run the restore command against any of the new servers:

Bash
consul snapshot restore backup.snap
Note: If ACLs were enabled on the old cluster, you must pass a valid management token from the old cluster into this command, as the snapshot contains the old ACL state.

Which should you choose?
As a best practice, if you have intact data directories, Option 1 (peers.json) is the gold standard. It guarantees you lose zero state (no missing KV updates, no dropped service registrations) and brings the cluster back exactly as it was the moment before the crash, just on new hardware. Option 2 is a great fallback if the data directories got corrupted during the crash.

so are you sure that for Option 2 i.e the Snapshot method it will work on the cluster with new ips?

Yes, I am 100% sure that Option 2 (the Snapshot method) will work perfectly on a new cluster with brand-new IP addresses. To understand why this is guaranteed to work, we have to look at the difference between Raft configuration and the State Machine in Consul.

Why the Snapshot Method Works seamlessly with New IPs
When you use Option 2, you are executing a two-step process that completely bypasses the IP-binding issues:

Step 1: You build a healthy, blank cluster first
Because you start with completely empty data directories on the new servers, they have no historical memory of the old IPs. They bootstrap using their new configurations, find each other via the new IPs (using retry_join), successfully form a Raft quorum, and elect a brand-new leader.

At this exact moment, you have a fully functional, empty Consul cluster running on the new IPs.

Step 2: You stream the state onto the active leader
When you run consul snapshot restore backup.snap:

You are sending the backup file to the newly elected leader of your new cluster via the HTTP API.

The snapshot contains the State Machine data (all your KV pairs, ACL tokens, service registrations, and intentions). It does not overwrite the physical, active network topology of your running cluster.

The new leader takes this data, writes it to its database, and replicates it to its current followers (the other new servers) using the active, healthy connection paths they already established in Step 1.

The old IP addresses of the dead servers are never introduced to the new cluster's routing table.

Why this is different from copying the Data Directory (Method 2)
Feature	Copying Data Directory	Restoring a Snapshot
What is copied?	The raw, physical Raft database files.	A logical export of the Consul state.
Contains Old IPs?	Yes. The physical Raft metadata database has the old IPs hardcoded into its peer logs.	No. It contains the data processed by Raft, but not the physical connection logs.
How Quorum is formed	The servers boot up blindly trying to reach the old IPs to form a cluster. (Fails on new IPs without peers.json)	The servers form a clean cluster first, then import the data. (Succeeds automatically)
Summary
If you want the fastest, zero-friction recovery and you don't mind losing whatever small amount of data was written between your last snapshot and the crash, Option 2 is the easiest way to recover onto new IPs.

Also lets say I am going with option 2 and I do not have bootstrap token avaialble, what will I do then?

If you choose Option 2 (The Snapshot Method) and you do not have the old bootstrap token (or any management token) available, you will run into a classic "chicken-and-egg" security lockout:

If you bootstrap the new cluster with ACLs strictly enabled (default_policy = "deny"), it will reject your consul snapshot restore command with a 403 (Permission Denied) because you don't have a token to authorize the restore.

If you bootstrap the cluster with ACLs temporarily disabled to force the restore through, the moment you turn ACLs back on, you will be completely locked out because the restored snapshot contains the old ACL database, and you don't have the key to open it.

Fortunately, there is a battle-tested "Break-In" Recovery Procedure designed specifically for this exact situation.

Step-by-Step Recovery Procedure (No Token + New IPs)
Phase 1: Restore the Snapshot in "Permissive" Mode
To bypass the initial token requirement, we will temporarily start the new cluster in a state that allows us to import the snapshot, and then lock it down.

Configure the 3 new servers with ACLs set to "allow":
In your Consul server configurations, set the default policy to allow, and explicitly do not set any master tokens:

Terraform
acl {
  enabled        = true
  default_policy = "allow" # Temporarily allow everything
}
Start the new cluster:
Let the 3 new servers boot up with empty data directories. They will automatically form a clean quorum on their new IP addresses.

Restore your snapshot:
Since the cluster is in permissive mode, it does not require a token to perform administrative operations. Run the restore command from any server:

Bash
consul snapshot restore backup.snap
At this point, all of your historical KV data, services, and policies are safely loaded into the active database.

Phase 2: Force-Reset the ACL System to Generate a New Token
Now that your data is restored, you need to lock the cluster down and generate a fresh master token to replace the lost one.

Enforce strict security:
Change your server configuration files back to your strict production settings:

Terraform
acl {
  enabled        = true
  default_policy = "deny" # Change back to deny
}
Perform a rolling restart of your 3 Consul servers. Once restarted, the cluster is secure, and you are officially locked out.

Find the current leader:
The ACL bypass mechanism must be executed on the active cluster leader. Find the leader's IP address:

Bash
curl http://127.0.0.1:8500/v1/status/leader
# Output example: "192.168.1.10:8300"
Log into the server that matches that IP address.

Trigger the bootstrap error to find the Reset Index:
On the leader server, attempt to run the bootstrap command. Because a snapshot was restored, Consul knows ACLs have been bootstrapped in the past and will block you, but it will give you a crucial piece of information:

Bash
consul acl bootstrap
Expected Output:

Plaintext
Failed ACL bootstrapping: Unexpected response code: 403 (Permission denied: ACL bootstrap no longer allowed (reset index: 142))
Write down that reset index (in this example, 142).

Write the Reset Index to Disk:
To prove to Consul's internal database that you have physical root access to the server, write that index number to a special file called acl-bootstrap-reset inside the Consul data directory:

Bash
echo 142 > /opt/consul/acl-bootstrap-reset
Generate your new Master Token:
Run the bootstrap command on the leader node once more:

Bash
consul acl bootstrap
The Result
Consul will detect the acl-bootstrap-reset file on disk, verify the index number matches, bypass the safety lock, and output a brand-new Global Management Token:

Plaintext
AccessorID:   e85b9b9a-4c28-9d43-09ef-d4928f6412ab
SecretID:     a23b8f2d-df71-46bb-be0c-51928374a9bc
Description:  Bootstrap Token (Global Management)
Local:        false
Create Time:  2026-07-10 17:45:00 +0000 UTC
Policies:
   00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001 (global-management)
Consul will automatically delete the acl-bootstrap-reset file from your disk for security. You can now export this new SecretID as your CONSUL_HTTP_TOKEN and resume managing your fully recovered cluster!

tell me does :

acl {
  enabled  = true
  default_policy = "allow" # Temporarily allow everything
}

is same as:
acl {
  enabled = false
}. ??

No, they are not the same. While both configurations allow actions to succeed without being blocked, they behave fundamentally differently under the hood.

Here is the exact difference:

1. enabled = true with default_policy = "allow" (ACLs are ON, but permissive)
The ACL engine is fully active. Consul is actively processing policies and tokens.

If a request is made with a valid token, Consul evaluates it. If a request has no token, it falls back to the default policy, which is to allow it.

Why this matters for recovery: Because the ACL engine is running, you can interact with the ACL APIs. You can create tokens, resolve existing tokens, and most importantly, run the consul acl bootstrap command to generate a new management token.

2. enabled = false (ACLs are completely OFF)
The ACL engine is shut down. Consul completely ignores tokens, policies, and security rules.

All API endpoints and agent communications are completely wide open.

Why this is a problem for recovery: Because the ACL engine is completely disabled, all ACL-related CLI commands and API endpoints are blocked. If you run consul acl bootstrap, Consul will return an error stating that ACLs are disabled on the agent. You cannot generate new tokens or manage policies in this state.


